    "Physics Constraints": "1. Conservative Weak-Form Residuals: Enforce integral conservation laws using test functions to avoid differentiating discontinuous fields. 2. Entropy Condition: Enforce an entropy inequality or add entropy-viscosity regularization to prevent unphysical expansion shocks. 3. Positivity Constraints: Strictly enforce ρ > 0 and p > 0 via logarithmic network outputs or soft penalty terms to prevent solver collapse. 4. Rankine-Hugoniot Conditions: Implicitly satisfied via the weak-form integral constraints across subdomain interfaces.",
    "Model Choice": "A Conservative Physics-Informed Neural Network (cPINN) combined with Causal Training. Standard strong-form PINNs fail on hyperbolic conservation laws due to Gibbs phenomena and invalid point-wise derivatives at shocks. cPINN decomposes the domain into subdomains, enforcing flux continuity at interfaces. Causal training respects the temporal causality of hyperbolic PDEs, preventing the network from fitting future shock positions before the initial wave propagation is resolved. The base architecture is a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) with adaptive activation functions to capture sharp gradients.",
    "Training Strategy": "1. Loss Function: Weighted sum of weak-form PDE residuals, interface flux continuity, initial condition matching, and positivity penalties. 2. Sampling: Adaptive collocation point sampling concentrated near high-gradient regions (shocks/contacts) using gradient-based error indicators. Causal time-marching sampling to sequentially unlock temporal domains. 3. Optimization: Adam optimizer for initial convergence, followed by L-BFGS. Use Neural Tangent Kernel (NTK) based adaptive loss weighting to balance gradient pathologies between IC and PDE residuals. 4. Stabilization: Introduce artificial entropy viscosity during early training to smooth shocks, gradually annealing it to zero to recover sharp fronts.",
