  "answer": {
    "Problem Formalization": "Solve the complex-valued Helmholtz equation ∇²u + k²u = f(x,y) in a bounded 2D domain Ω, where u: Ω → ℂ, k = 2π/λ is the wavenumber, and f is a known source term. The domain spans L ≈ 20λ in each direction, giving kL ≈ 40π. Boundary data u|∂Ω = g (or ∂u/∂n|∂Ω = h) is prescribed but the specific type (Dirichlet, Neumann, Robin, or mixed) is not stated; the workflow must accommodate any well-posed combination. The medium is assumed homogeneous (constant k) since no spatially varying coefficient field is specified; if k = k(x,y) were heterogeneous, the PDE residual would need to incorporate ∇k terms and the sampling density would need to increase near high-gradient regions of k. The exact domain geometry (rectangular vs. irregular) and source term form are also unspecified, which affects mesh generation and quadrature but not the core collocation strategy.",
    "Physics Constraints": "The PDE residual is R_pde = ∇²u + k²u − f, enforced as a complex-valued L² penalty |R_pde|² over Ω. Boundary residuals R_bc enforce the prescribed data on ∂Ω. Because u is complex-valued, the network outputs two real channels (Re(u), Im(u)) and all derivatives are computed via automatic differentiation on each channel independently. The high-frequency regime (kL ≈ 40π) introduces the pollution effect: numerical phase error accumulates over the domain, so the discretization must resolve not just the wavelength but also control dispersion error. Energy conservation (∫_Ω |∇u|² − k²|u|² dx = boundary flux terms) can serve as an auxiliary integral constraint to regularize training.",
    "Model Choice": "A domain-decomposed Fourier-feature Physics-Informed Neural Network (XPINN with Fourier embeddings). The domain is partitioned into a 4×4 grid of 16 overlapping subdomains, each spanning ~5λ × 5λ, reducing the effective kL per subdomain to ~10π and mitigating the highly non-convex loss landscape of a single global network. Each subdomain network uses a Fourier-feature input layer with frequencies sampled from a Gaussian distribution scaled to k (i.e., σ = k/(2π) = 1/λ), followed by a 6-layer MLP of width 128 with tanh activations, outputting (Re(u), Im(u)). Fourier features directly address the spectral bias of standard MLPs, which otherwise suppress high-frequency content. Domain decomposition localizes phase errors and enables parallel training. Interface continuity (u and ∂u/∂n matching across subdomain boundaries) is enforced via penalty terms on overlap regions.",
    "Training Strategy": "Sampling: 15 collocation points per wavelength in each spatial direction. With L = 20λ, this yields 20 × 15 = 300 points per direction, for a total of 300 × 300 = 90,000 collocation points across the full domain (distributed as ~5,625 interior points per subdomain plus boundary and interface points). This 15 ppw figure exceeds the Nyquist rate (2 ppw) sufficiently to control dispersion error in the second-order PDE residual computed via automatic differentiation. Loss: L = λ_pde ‖R_pde‖² + λ_bc ‖R_bc‖² + λ_intf ‖R_interface‖², with weights initialized via Neural Tangent Kernel (NTK) balancing to equalize convergence rates across loss terms. Optimizer: Adam (lr = 1e-4) for 50,000 epochs followed by L-BFGS for fine convergence. Curriculum: begin training at k_eff = k/4 and double k_eff every 10,000 epochs until the target k is reached, guiding the network through progressively harder loss landscapes. Boundary points are sampled at 20 ppw along ∂Ω to ensure boundary data is well-resolved.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "1) Phase wrapping and accumulation: even small per-wavelength phase errors compound over 20 wavelengths, leading to completely incorrect phase fields despite low local residual; mitigate by monitoring phase error against an analytical or reference solution at multiple interior probes. 2) Spectral bias resurgence: if Fourier feature frequencies are poorly scaled (σ ≪ 1/λ), the network will still damp high-frequency content, producing smooth but wrong solutions; validate by checking the power spectrum of the predicted u against expected k-content. 3) Loss landscape local minima: high-frequency Helmholtz has exponentially many spurious stationary points; curriculum learning and domain decomposition reduce but do not eliminate this risk — multiple random restarts may be needed. 4) Interface inconsistency: in domain decomposition, imperfect continuity enforcement can create artificial reflections at subdomain boundaries, visible as discontinuities in |u| or phase jumps; monitor interface residuals separately and increase overlap width if needed. 5) Insufficient collocation density: 15 ppw may be marginal for automatic-differentiation-based second derivatives, which amplify high-frequency noise; if validation shows noisy ∇²u fields, increase to 20 ppw (total budget 160,000 points). 6) Missing physics: if the unspecified boundary conditions include absorbing/radiation conditions (e.g., Sommerfeld), failing to implement them correctly will produce unphysical standing-wave artifacts."
