    "Physics Constraints": "(i) IC enforcement: u(x,0) = sin(πx) is enforced via an L2 penalty on collocation points sampled at t=0. The velocity IC u_t(x,0) = 0.1cos(πx) requires derivative-level treatment: automatic differentiation computes ∂u/∂t from the network output at t=0, and an L2 penalty enforces agreement with 0.1cos(πx). (ii) Corner compatibility at (0,0): the two deciding numeric values are the initial velocity at the endpoint u_t(0,0) = 0.1cos(0) = 0.1 and the time derivative of the boundary condition ∂_t[u(0,t)] = ∂_t[0] = 0. These do NOT match (0.1 ≠ 0). The workflow handles this by: (a) excluding the exact corner points (0,0) and (1,0) from both IC and BC loss sampling to avoid conflicting gradient signals; (b) concentrating adaptive collocation points along the characteristic line x = ct emanating from (0,0), along which the mismatch propagates; (c) using a weak-form or gradient-enhanced PDE loss near this line to accommodate the discontinuity. The corner mismatch propagates along the characteristic x - ct = 0 (i.e., x = ct) and carries a velocity discontinuity of magnitude |0.1 - 0| = 0.1 (the jump in u_t across x = ct is exactly 0.1). A symmetric mismatch exists at (1,0) where u_t(1,0) = -0.1 ≠ 0, propagating along x + ct = 1. Validation detects the propagating defect by: evaluating the PDE residual profile along x = ct (expecting elevated but bounded residuals), and directly computing the jump [u_t(ct+ε,t) - u_t(ct-ε,t)] for small ε, verifying it approximates 0.1. (iii) Physical invariant: total mechanical energy E(t) = ½∫₀¹[u_t(x,t)² + c²u_x(x,t)²]dx, which is conserved for the linear wave equation even with weak solutions. E(0) = (0.01 + c²π²)/4. Monitor relative deviation |E(t) - E(0)|/E(0) with tolerance ≤ 2%.",
    "Model Choice": "Physics-Informed Neural Network (PINN) with a fully connected architecture (6-8 hidden layers, 64-128 neurons per layer). Sine or periodic activation functions are preferred to naturally represent the oscillatory wave modes and to better resolve sharp gradients near discontinuities compared to tanh/ReLU. Soft enforcement of BCs and ICs via penalty terms is chosen over hard encoding because no smooth ansatz can simultaneously satisfy the incompatible corner conditions; hard encoding would artificially smooth the singularity. For improved discontinuity capture, a domain-decomposition variant (XPINN) is recommended: partition the space-time domain into subdomains separated by the characteristic lines x = ct and x + ct = 1, with independent networks per subdomain and interface continuity conditions on u (but allowing u_t jumps). This isolates the discontinuity to subdomain boundaries where it can be explicitly represented.",
    "Training Strategy": "Composite loss: L = λ_pde·L_pde + λ_ic_u·L_ic_u + λ_ic_ut·L_ic_ut + λ_bc·L_bc. L_pde = MSE(u_tt - c²u_xx, 0) on ~10,000 interior collocation points. L_ic_u = MSE(u(x,0), sin(πx)) on ~500 points at t=0. L_ic_ut = MSE(∂_t u(x,0), 0.1cos(πx)) on ~500 points at t=0 via autodiff. L_bc = MSE(u(0,t), 0) + MSE(u(1,t), 0) on ~500 points per boundary. Corner points (0,0) and (1,0) are explicitly excluded from all boundary and initial sampling sets. Adaptive residual-based sampling (e.g., RAR or importance sampling) is applied every 1000 epochs to concentrate new collocation points near the characteristics x = ct and x + ct = 1 where PDE residuals are highest. Two-phase optimization: Adam optimizer (lr=1e-3, 5000-10000 epochs) for initial convergence, followed by L-BFGS (tolerance 1e-6) for high-accuracy refinement. Loss weights are initialized via neural tangent kernel (NTK) balancing or learning-rate annealing to prevent gradient pathology between PDE, IC, and BC terms. If using XPINN, interface loss terms enforce continuity of u across subdomain boundaries while permitting discontinuous u_t.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "1. Discontinuity smearing: the network may predict a smooth transition across x = ct instead of the sharp velocity jump of 0.1, leading to incorrect physics. Detected by computing u_t at (ct±ε, t) and verifying |jump - 0.1| < 0.05. 2. Gibbs-like oscillations: spurious high-frequency oscillations near the characteristic lines due to the network attempting to fit a discontinuous solution with smooth basis functions. Detected by inspecting u_xx profiles and checking for non-physical overshoots. 3. Energy drift: failure to conserve E(t) indicates the network has not learned the correct weak solution. Flagged if |E(t) - E(0)|/E(0) > 2% at any validation time. 4. Incorrect wave speed propagation: the discontinuity locations may drift from x = ct and x = 1-ct if the network fails to learn the correct characteristic structure. Detected by tracking the locus of maximum |u_xx| over time and verifying it follows the theoretical characteristics. 5. Loss imbalance: over-satisfaction of IC/BC at the expense of PDE residual (or vice versa), producing a solution that satisfies constraints but violates physics. Mitigated by NTK-based weight balancing and monitoring all loss components independently. 6. Corner singularity contamination: including corner points in both IC and BC losses creates irreconcilable gradient conflicts that destabilize training. Mitigated by explicit exclusion of (0,0) and (1,0) from sampling."
  }
}

